B044C023V019	44	23	19	And the commander, taking him by his hand, withdrew to a private place and inquired, "What is it that you have to tell me?"
B044C023V020	44	23	20	And he said, "The Jews have agreed to ask that tomorrow you bring Paul down to the Sanhedrin, as though they are going to learn something more accurate concerning him.
B044C023V021	44	23	21	Therefore you [must] not be persuaded by them; for more than four hundred of them are lying in wait for him, who have bound themselves by a curse neither to eat nor to drink until they kill him; and now they are prepared, waiting for the promise from you."
B044C023V022	44	23	22	Then the commander dismissed the young man, and commanded him, "Tell no one that you have made known these things to me."
B044C023V023	44	23	23	And having summoned two of the centurions he said, "Make ready two hundred soldiers, and seventy horsemen, and two hundred spearmen, in order that they may go to Caesarea, to leave at the third hour of the night;
B044C023V024	44	23	24	and place mounts at [their] disposal, in order that they may put Paul on them, and bring him safely to Felix the governor."
B044C023V025	44	23	25	And he wrote a letter which contained this content:
B044C023V026	44	23	26	Claudius Lysias, to the most excellent governor Felix: Greetings.
B044C023V027	44	23	27	This man, having been arrested by the Jews, was about to be killed by them. I came upon [them] with the detachment of soldiers and rescued him, having learned that he is a Roman.
B044C023V028	44	23	28	And desiring to know the cause for which they were accusing him, I took him down to their council;
B044C023V029	44	23	29	and I found that he was accused concerning questions of their law, [but] had no accusation [against him] worthy of death or chains.
B044C023V030	44	23	30	And when it became known to me that a plot against the man by the Jews was about to happen, I sent him at once to you, and also commanded the accusers to state the charges against him before you. Farewell.
B044C023V031	44	23	31	Then the soldiers, as they were commanded, took Paul and brought him during the night to Antipatris.
B044C023V032	44	23	32	And on the next day they left the horsemen to go on with him, and returned to the barracks.
B044C023V033	44	23	33	When they entered into Caesarea and delivered the letter to the governor, [they] also presented Paul to him.
B044C023V034	44	23	34	And when the governor read the letter, he asked what province he was from. And learning that he was from Cilicia,
B044C023V035	44	23	35	he said, "I will give you a hearing when your accusers arrive."And he commanded him to be guarded in Herod's Praetorium.
B044C024V001	44	24	1	Now after five days Ananias the high priest came down with the elders and a certain attorney named Tertullus, who made known to the governor the charges against Paul.
B044C024V002	44	24	2	And when he had been called, Tertullus began to accuse [him], saying: "Attaining much peace by you and successes coming about for this nation by your foresight,
B044C024V003	44	24	3	both in everything and everywhere we accept [it], most excellent Felix, with all thanksgiving.
B044C024V004	44	24	4	But that I not weary you any longer, I beseech you to hear us briefly in your graciousness.
B044C024V005	44	24	5	For [we] have found this man [to ]be a plague, and [one] causing discord among all the Jews throughout the world, and a leader of the Nazarenes sect,
B044C024V006	44	24	6	who also attempted to profane the temple, whom we also arrested,
B044C024V007	44	24	7	- - -
B044C024V008	44	24	8	from whom you will be able, having judged [him] yourself, to learn about all these things of which we are accusing him."
B044C024V009	44	24	9	And the Jews also joined in the attack, asserting that these things were so.
B044C024V010	44	24	10	But Paul answered (the governor, having nodded for him to speak): "Knowing that you have been a judge of this nation for many years, the more cheerfully I defend the things concerning myself,
B044C024V011	44	24	11	because you being able to know that it has not been more than twelve days since I went up to worship in Jerusalem.
B044C024V012	44	24	12	And they did not find me with anyone in the temple disputing, or inciting a crowd to rise up, neither in the synagogues nor in the city.
B044C024V013	44	24	13	Nor are they able to prove [against ]me the things about which they are now accusing me.
B044C024V014	44	24	14	But I confess this to you, that according to the Way which they call a sect, so I worship the God of my fathers, believing in all things which are written throughout the Law and in the Prophets,
B044C024V015	44	24	15	having hope in God, which even they themselves are waiting for, that there is going to be a resurrection of the dead, both of the just and the unjust.
B044C024V016	44	24	16	And in this I myself am engaging, having a conscience blameless toward God and men through everything.
B044C024V017	44	24	17	And after many years I arrived to bring alms and offerings to my nation,
B044C024V018	44	24	18	among whom some Jews from Asia found me, having been purified in the temple, not with a crowd nor with turmoil,
B044C024V019	44	24	19	who ought to be present before you and to make accusation if anything they might have against me.
B044C024V020	44	24	20	Or let these themselves say what wrong they found in me, when I stood before the council,
B044C024V021	44	24	21	unless it is because of this one statement which I cried out, standing among them, 'Concerning the resurrection of the dead I am being judged by you today.' "
B044C024V022	44	24	22	And when he heard these things, Felix adjourned them, knowing more accurately the things[ ]concerning the Way, and said, "When Lysias the commander comes down, I will decide your case."
B044C024V023	44	24	23	And ordering the centurion to keep watch over Paul and to let him have some liberty, and not to forbid [any] of his own to serve or to come to him.
B044C024V024	44	24	24	Now after some days, when Felix arrived with Drusilla his wife, who was Jewish, he sent for Paul and heard him concerning the faith in Christ.
B044C024V025	44	24	25	And as he reasoned about righteousness, self-control, and the judgment which is going to be, Felix became afraid and answered, "Go away for now; but when I have opportunity I will summon you."
B044C024V026	44	24	26	Meanwhile he also hoped that money would be given him by Paul, that he might release him. Therefore sending for him more often, he was conversing with him.
B044C024V027	44	24	27	But after two years had passed, Felix received Porcius Festus as his successor; and Felix, desiring to grant favors to the Jews, left Paul in prison.
B044C025V001	44	25	1	Now when Festus had set foot in the province, after three days he went up to Jerusalem from Ceasarea.
B044C025V002	44	25	2	And the high priest and the prominent men of the Jews made known to him the case against Paul; and they were appealing to him,
B044C025V003	44	25	3	asking for favor against him, that he would summon him to Jerusalem-while planning an ambush to kill him along the way.
B044C025V004	44	25	4	But Festus answered that Paul should be kept at Caesarea, and that he was about to go there shortly.
B044C025V005	44	25	5	"Therefore,"he said, "the prominent men among you, let them go with me and accuse this man, if there is anything in this man."
B044C025V006	44	25	6	And when he had stayed among them more than ten days, he went down to Caesarea. And the next day, sitting on the judgment seat, he commanded Paul to be brought.
B044C025V007	44	25	7	When he arrived, the Jews who had come down from Jerusalem stood around him, bringing many and serious accusations against Paul, which they were not able to prove,
B044C025V008	44	25	8	while he defended himself, [saying,] "Neither against the law of the Jews, nor against the temple, nor against Caesar did I commit any sin."
B044C025V009	44	25	9	But Festus, desiring to grant a favor to the Jews, answered Paul and said, "Are you willing to go up to Jerusalem and there be judged before me concerning these things?"
B044C025V010	44	25	10	But Paul said, "I am standing before the judicial bench of Caesar, by whom it is necessary [for] me to be judged. I have done no wrong to the Jews, as also you know very well.
B044C025V011	44	25	11	For if I am doing wrong, and have done anything worthy of death, I am not trying to escape a death sentence; but if there is nothing in these things of which these [people] are accusing me, no one is able to deliver me to them. I appeal to Caesar."
B044C025V012	44	25	12	Then Festus, having talked together with the council, answered, "Have you appealed to Caesar? Before Caesar you shall go!"
B044C025V013	44	25	13	And after some days King Agrippa and Bernice arrived in Caesarea and greeted Festus.
B044C025V014	44	25	14	And as he was spending many days there, Festus laid before the king the charges against Paul, saying: "There is a certain man who was left a prisoner by Felix,
B044C025V015	44	25	15	about whom the chief priests and the elders of the Jews informed me, when I was in Jerusalem, asking for punishment against him.
B044C025V016	44	25	16	To them I answered, 'It is not a custom with Romans to deliver any man to destruction before the [one] being accused may meet his accusers face to face, and may receive an opportunity for defense concerning the charge.'
B044C025V017	44	25	17	"Therefore when they had assembled here, having made no delay, on the next day I took my seat at the judicial bench, and I commanded the man to be brought [in];
B044C025V018	44	25	18	concerning whom, when the accusers stood, they brought no accusation of the[ ]things which I was supposing,
B044C025V019	44	25	19	but had some questions against him about their own religion and about a certain Jesus, who had died, whom Paul affirmed to be living.
B044C025V020	44	25	20	And being uncertain [as to] the investigation concerning this, I asked whether he was willing to go to Jerusalem and there be judged concerning these charges.
B044C025V021	44	25	21	But when Paul appealed that he be kept for the decision of His Majesty the Emperor, I commanded him to be kept until I may send him to Caesar."
B044C025V022	44	25	22	Then Agrippa said to Festus, "I also was wishing to hear the man myself.""Tomorrow,"he said, "you shall hear him."
B044C025V023	44	25	23	Therefore on the next day, when Agrippa and Bernice had come with all pomp, and had entered into the auditorium together with the commanders and the prominent men of the city, and when Festus had commanded, Paul was brought.
B044C025V024	44	25	24	And Festus said: "King Agrippa and all the men who are with us, observe this man about whom the people of the Jews petitioned me, both in Jerusalem and here, crying against [him] that it is not fitting [for] him to live any longer.
B044C025V025	44	25	25	But when I came to understand him to have done nothing worthy of death, and also he had appealed to His Majesty the Emperor, I decided to send him.
B044C025V026	44	25	26	About whom I have nothing certain to write to my lord. Therefore I have brought him before you, and especially before you King Agrippa, in order that when this hearing is finished I may have something to write.
B044C025V027	44	25	27	For it seems unreasonable to me to send a prisoner and not to signify the accusations against him."
B044C026V001	44	26	1	Then Agrippa said to Paul, "It is permitted for you to speak for yourself."So Paul, having extended his hand, spoke in his own defense:
B044C026V002	44	26	2	I have considered myself fortunate, King Agrippa, being able to speak in my own defense today, concerning all the things of which I am accused of by the Jews,
B044C026V003	44	26	3	especially since you are well versed both in all the customs and questions in relation to the Jews; therefore I beg you to hear me patiently.
B044C026V004	44	26	4	Therefore my way of life from my youth, which from the beginning was spent among my own nation in Jerusalem, all the Jews know,
B044C026V005	44	26	5	since they have known me for a long time, if they are willing to testify, that according to the strictest sect of our religion I lived a Pharisee.
B044C026V006	44	26	6	And now for the hope of the promise having been made by God to the fathers, I stand before you judged,
B044C026V007	44	26	7	[a promise] to which our twelve tribes, as they earnestly serve God night and day, hope to attain. Concerning which hope I am accused by [the] Jews, King Agrippa.
B044C026V008	44	26	8	Why is it considered [such ]an unbelievable thing by you [people ]if God raises the dead?
B044C026V009	44	26	9	Therefore I thought in myself that it was necessary to do many hostile things against the name of Jesus the Nazarene;
B044C026V010	44	26	10	which also I did in Jerusalem, and many of the saints I shut up in prisons, having received authority from the chief priests; and when they were being put to death, I cast my vote against them.
B044C026V011	44	26	11	And I punished them often in all the synagogues, and compelled them to blaspheme; and being exceedingly enraged against them, I persecuted them even as far as to foreign cities.
B044C026V012	44	26	12	"In which [pursuits] also, as I traveled to Damascus with authority and commission from the chief priests,
B044C026V013	44	26	13	at midday, O king, along the road I saw a light from heaven, brighter than the sun, shining around me and those traveling with me.
B044C026V014	44	26	14	And when we all had fallen down to the ground, I heard a voice speaking to me and saying in the Hebrew language, 'Saul, Saul, why are you persecuting Me? It is hard for you to kick against the goads.'
B044C026V015	44	26	15	"So I said, 'Who are You, Lord?' And He said, 'I am Jesus, whom you are persecuting.
B044C026V016	44	26	16	But arise and stand on your feet; for I have appeared to you, to appoint you a minister and a witness both [of the things] which you have seen, and [of the things] which I will yet reveal to you,
B044C026V017	44	26	17	delivering you from the people, and from the Gentiles, to whom I am sending you,
B044C026V018	44	26	18	to open their eyes, in order to turn them from darkness to light, and from the authority of Satan to God, [in order for ]them to receive forgiveness of sins and an inheritance among those who are sanctified by faith in Me.'
B044C026V019	44	26	19	"Therefore, King Agrippa, I was not disobedient to the heavenly vision,
B044C026V020	44	26	20	but to those first in Damascus and in Jerusalem, and throughout all the region of Judea, and to the Gentiles, proclaiming that they must repent and turn to God, and do works worthy of repentance.
B044C026V021	44	26	21	Because of these things the Jews arrested me in the temple and attempted to kill me.
B044C026V022	44	26	22	Therefore, having obtained help from God, until this day I stand, witnessing both to common [people] and great [people], saying nothing except the things which both the prophets and Moses spoke of as being about to happen,
B044C026V023	44	26	23	that the Christ was to suffer, that as the first to rise from the dead, He was about to proclaim light to the Jewish people and to the Gentiles."
B044C026V024	44	26	24	Now as he spoke these things, Festus said with a loud voice, "You are mad, Paul! Your higher learning is driving you to madness!"
B044C026V025	44	26	25	But he said, "I am not mad, most excellent Festus, but I boldly declare words of truth and reason.
B044C026V026	44	26	26	For the king knows about these things, to whom also I speak freely; for I am persuaded that none of these things escapes his notice, since this thing was not done in a corner.
B044C026V027	44	26	27	"Do you believe the prophets, King Agrippa? I know that you believe."
B044C026V028	44	26	28	And Agrippa said to Paul, "In a short time, you are persuading me to become a Christian!"
B044C026V029	44	26	29	And Paul said, "I would pray to God, both in a short time and a long time, not only you, but also all who are hearing me today, would become such as I am, except for these chains."
B044C026V030	44	26	30	When he had said these things, the king stood up, as well as the governor and Bernice and those sitting together with them;
B044C026V031	44	26	31	and when they withdrew, they were speaking among themselves, saying, "This man practices nothing worthy of death or chains."
B044C026V032	44	26	32	Then Agrippa said to Festus, "This man could have been released if he had not appealed to Caesar."
B044C027V001	44	27	1	Now when it was decided that we should sail away to Italy, they handed over both Paul and certain other prisoners to a centurion named Julius, of the Augustan Regiment.
B044C027V002	44	27	2	And having boarded a ship of Adramyttium, scheduled to sail to the ports along the Asian coasts, we put to sea. Aristarchus, a Macedonian of Thessalonica, being with us.
B044C027V003	44	27	3	And the next day we put in to harbor at Sidon. And Julius treated Paul kindly, and permitted [him] to go to [his] friends to find care.
B044C027V004	44	27	4	And from there having put to sea, we sailed under the sheltered side of Cyprus, because the winds were against us.
B044C027V005	44	27	5	And having sailed across the sea which is off Cilicia and Pamphylia, we docked at Myra, in Lycia.
B044C027V006	44	27	6	And there the centurion found an Alexandrian ship sailing to Italy, and he put us aboard in it.
B044C027V007	44	27	7	And sailing slowly many days, and with difficulty arriving down off Cnidus, since the wind would not permit us to go on, we sailed under the sheltered side of Crete, down off Salmone.
B044C027V008	44	27	8	And with difficulty sailing past it, we came to a place called Fair Havens, near the city of Lasea.
B044C027V009	44	27	9	Now when much time had been spent, the voyage having already become dangerous, because the Fast had already gone by, Paul recommended,
B044C027V010	44	27	10	saying to them, "Men, I perceive this voyage is going to be with hardship and much loss, not only of the cargo and of the ship but also our lives."
B044C027V011	44	27	11	But the centurion was persuaded by the helmsman and the ship owner, rather than by the things being said by Paul.
B044C027V012	44	27	12	And because the harbor was not suitable to winter in, the majority gave counsel to put to sea from there, if perhaps they might be able to get to Phoenix to spend the winter there, a harbor of Crete opening toward the southwest and to the northwest.
B044C027V013	44	27	13	And when a south wind blew gently, supposing they had attained their purpose, they weighed anchor and sailed along close in shore to Crete.
B044C027V014	44	27	14	But not long after, a head wind like a hurricane arose, called [a ]Euroclydon;
B044C027V015	44	27	15	and when the ship was seized by it, and not being able to face into the wind, we were being driven along, [having ]given in [to the wind.]
B044C027V016	44	27	16	And running under the sheltered side of a certain little island called Clauda, we secured the skiff with difficulty.
B044C027V017	44	27	17	And having hoisted it up, they used cables for undergirding the ship; and being afraid lest they run aground in the Syrtes [Shallows], they let down the driving anchor, thus they were being driven along [by the wind.]
B044C027V018	44	27	18	And because we were exceedingly tempest-tossed, the next day they lightened the ship.
B044C027V019	44	27	19	And on the third day we threw off the equipment of the ship with our own hands.
B044C027V020	44	27	20	And neither the sun nor stars appeared for many days, and no small storm pressed on us, finally all hope for us to be saved was taken away.
B044C027V021	44	27	21	Now when they had abstained from food for a long time, then stood Paul in the midst of them and said, "Men, you should have followed my advice and not put to sea from Crete, and to spare [yourselves ]this hardship and loss.
B044C027V022	44	27	22	And now I urge you to keep up [your] courage, for there will be loss of not one life among you, only of the ship.
B044C027V023	44	27	23	For there stood by me this night an angel of the God to whom I belong, whom also I serve,
B044C027V024	44	27	24	saying, 'Do not be afraid, Paul; for it is necessary for you to stand before Caesar; and behold, God has granted you all those sailing with you.'
B044C027V025	44	27	25	"Therefore keep up your courage, men; for I believe God that it will be in the very manner it has been spoken to me.
B044C027V026	44	27	26	However, it is necessary [for] us to run aground on a certain island."
B044C027V027	44	27	27	Now when it was the fourteenth night, as we were driven about in the Adriatic Sea, in the middle of the night the sailors sensed that land was approaching them.
B044C027V028	44	27	28	And having taken a sounding, they found it to be twenty fathoms; and when they had gone a little farther, they took soundings again and found it to be fifteen fathoms;
B044C027V029	44	27	29	and being afraid lest we should run aground on the rocks, they threw out four anchors from the stern, and were praying for day to come.
B044C027V030	44	27	30	Now as the sailors were seeking to flee from the ship, and letting down the skiff into the sea, in pretense of spreading out anchors from the prow,
B044C027V031	44	27	31	Paul said to the centurion and the soldiers, "If these men do not remain in the ship, you cannot be saved."
B044C027V032	44	27	32	Then the soldiers cut off the ropes of the skiff and let it fall off.
B044C027V033	44	27	33	And until the [time] was about to be day, Paul was urging them all to receive their share of food, saying, "Today is the fourteenth day you continue waiting without eating, having taken nothing.
B044C027V034	44	27	34	Therefore I urge you to take food, for this is for your deliverance; for not a hair from your head shall fall."
B044C027V035	44	27	35	And having said these things and having taken bread, he gave thanks to God in the presence of all, and having broken it, he began to eat.
B044C027V036	44	27	36	And they all became cheerful and also took food themselves.
B044C027V037	44	27	37	And in all we were two hundred and seventy-six persons on the ship.
B044C027V038	44	27	38	And having eaten enough, they began lightening the ship and throwing out the wheat into the sea.
B044C027V039	44	27	39	Now when it became day, they did not recognize the land; but they noticed a certain bay which had a beach, on which they resolved, if possible, to run the ship ashore.
B044C027V040	44	27	40	And casting off the anchors, they were leaving them in the sea, meanwhile loosening the ropes of the rudders; and having raised the mainsail to the wind, they began steering toward the beach.
B044C027V041	44	27	41	But they struck a reef and ran the vessel aground, and the prow became stuck and remained unmoved, but the stern was being broken up by the violence of the waves.
B044C027V042	44	27	42	And the soldiers' decision was that they would kill the prisoners, lest any should swim away and escape.
B044C027V043	44	27	43	But the centurion, wanting to rescue Paul, hindered them in their intention, and commanded that those who were able to swim to jump down first to go toward the land,
B044C027V044	44	27	44	and the rest, some on boards and others on parts from the ship. And in this way it came about that all were brought to safety.
B044C028V001	44	28	1	And when they were rescued, then they learned that the island was called Malta.
B044C028V002	44	28	2	And the natives were showing us extraordinary kindness; for having kindled a fire they accepted us all into [their] society, because of the rain which had begun, and because of the cold.
B044C028V003	44	28	3	But when Paul had gathered a large bundle of sticks and put them on the fire, a viper having come out because of the heat, fastened on his hand.
B044C028V004	44	28	4	And when the natives saw the creature hanging from his hand, they said to one another, "Certainly this man is a murderer, whom though he was rescued from the sea, justice does not permit to continue living."
B044C028V005	44	28	5	Then, having shaken off the creature into the fire, he suffered nothing harmful.
B044C028V006	44	28	6	And they were expecting him to be about to swell up or suddenly fall down dead. But after they had waited for a long time and observed nothing unusual happening to him, they changed their minds and said that he was a god.
B044C028V007	44	28	7	Now in the areas around that place were pieces of land [belonging] to the leading citizen of the island, named Publius, who welcomed us, and received us hospitably as guests for three days.
B044C028V008	44	28	8	And it came to pass that the father of Publius lay sick of a fever and dysentery, to whom Paul came in and prayed, and laying his hands on him, healed him.
B044C028V009	44	28	9	Then after this happened, also the rest who were ill on the island were coming to him and were being healed,
B044C028V010	44	28	10	who also honored us with many honors, and when we put to sea, they gave us the things that we needed.
B044C028V011	44	28	11	Now after three months we put to sea in a ship that had wintered on the island, [belonging] to Alexandria, with the figurehead of the Twin Brothers.
B044C028V012	44	28	12	And putting in to harbor at Syracuse, we stayed there three days,
B044C028V013	44	28	13	from where having sailed around we arrived at Rhegium. And after one day arose a south wind, on the second day we came to Puteoli,
B044C028V014	44	28	14	where having found brothers, we were urged by them to stay for seven days; and so we came to Rome.
B044C028V015	44	28	15	And from there the brothers, when they heard about our circumstances, they came to meet with us as far as Appii Forum and Three Inns, whom when Paul saw, he gave thanks to God and took courage.
B044C028V016	44	28	16	Now when we came to Rome, the centurion handed over the prisoners to the captain of the guard; but Paul was allowed to stay by himself with the soldier guarding him.
B044C028V017	44	28	17	And it came to pass after three days that Paul called together those who were prominent among the Jews; and when they had come together, he said to them: "Men, brothers, though I have done nothing against the people or the customs of our forefathers, yet I was handed over as a prisoner from Jerusalem, into the hands of the Romans,
B044C028V018	44	28	18	who, when they had examined me, were wanting to release me because there was no cause for my case.
B044C028V019	44	28	19	But when the Jews spoke in opposition, I was compelled to appeal to Caesar, not that I had anything of which to accuse my nation.
B044C028V020	44	28	20	Therefore for this reason I have requested you, to see and to speak to you, for because of the hope of Israel I am wearing this chain."
B044C028V021	44	28	21	Then they said to him, "We neither received letters from Judea concerning you, nor have any of the brothers who arrived report or speak anything evil about you.
B044C028V022	44	28	22	But we request to hear from you the[ ]things which you think; for concerning this sect, it is known to us that everywhere it is spoken against."
B044C028V023	44	28	23	And having appointed for him a day, many came to him at his house, to whom he was explaining and solemnly testifying to the kingdom of God, and persuading them of the things concerning Jesus from both the Law of Moses and from the Prophets, from morning till evening.
B044C028V024	44	28	24	And some were persuaded by the things being said, but others refused to believe.
B044C028V025	44	28	25	And being in disagreement with one another, they went away after Paul had said one word: "The Holy Spirit spoke rightly through Isaiah the prophet to our fathers,
B044C028V026	44	28	26	saying, 'Go to this people and say: "Hearing you will hear, and by no means understand; and seeing you shall see, and by no means perceive;
B044C028V027	44	28	27	For the hearts of this people has become dull. Their ears are hard of hearing, and their eyes have closed, lest they should see with their eyes and they should hear with their ears, lest they should understand with their heart and turn back, so that I should heal them."'
B044C028V028	44	28	28	"Therefore let it be known to you that the salvation of God has been sent to the Gentiles, and they will hear it!"
B044C028V029	44	28	29	And when he had said these things, the Jews went away, having a great dispute among themselves.
B044C028V030	44	28	30	Then Paul remained two full years in his own rented house, and he was receiving all those who were coming to him,
B044C028V031	44	28	31	preaching the kingdom of God and teaching the things concerning the Lord Jesus Christ with all boldness, without hindrance.
B045C001V001	45	1	1	Paul, a bondservant of Jesus Christ, called [to be ]an apostle, having been separated unto the gospel of God
B045C001V002	45	1	2	which He promised beforehand through His prophets in the Holy Scriptures,
B045C001V003	45	1	3	concerning His Son, who came of [the] seed of David according to the flesh,
B045C001V004	45	1	4	who was declared Son of God with power according to the Spirit of holiness by the resurrection of [the] dead, Jesus Christ our Lord,
B045C001V005	45	1	5	through whom we received grace and apostleship for [the ]obedience of faith among all the nations for His name,
B045C001V006	45	1	6	among whom you also are the called of Jesus Christ:
B045C001V007	45	1	7	To all those who are in Rome, beloved of God, called [to be] saints: Grace to you and peace from God our Father and the Lord Jesus Christ.
B045C001V008	45	1	8	First, I thank my God through Jesus Christ for you all, that your faith is spoken of throughout the whole world.
B045C001V009	45	1	9	For God is my witness, whom I serve with my spirit in the gospel of His Son, that without ceasing I make mention of you always in my prayers,
B045C001V010	45	1	10	requesting if somehow now at sometime I shall succeed in the will of God to come to you.
B045C001V011	45	1	11	For I long to see you, so that I may impart to you some spiritual gift, that you may be established-
B045C001V012	45	1	12	that is, that I may be encouraged together with you through the mutual faith both of you and me.
B045C001V013	45	1	13	Now I do not want you to be ignorant, brothers, that often I planned to come to you (and I was hindered until now), that I might have some fruit among you also, just as among the other Gentiles.
B045C001V014	45	1	14	I am a debtor both to Greeks and to barbarians, both to [the ]wise and to [the ]unwise.
B045C001V015	45	1	15	So, as much as is in me, I am eager to preach the gospel to you who are in Rome also.
B045C001V016	45	1	16	For I am not ashamed of the gospel of Christ, for it is the power of God unto salvation to everyone that believes, both to the Jew first and to the Greek.
B045C001V017	45	1	17	For in it [the] righteousness of God is revealed from faith to faith; as it is written, "The just shall live by faith."
B045C001V018	45	1	18	For the wrath of God is revealed from heaven upon all ungodliness and unrighteousness of men who suppress the truth in unrighteousness.
B045C001V019	45	1	19	Because that which is known of God is manifest in them, for God has shown [it] to them.
B045C001V020	45	1	20	For the invisible things of Him from the creation of[ ]the world are clearly seen, being understood by the things made, both His eternal power and divinity, so that they are without excuse.
B045C001V021	45	1	21	Because, having known God, they did not glorify [Him] as God, or give thanks, but became vain in their reasonings, and their foolish heart was darkened.
B045C001V022	45	1	22	Asserting themselves to be wise, they became fools,
B045C001V023	45	1	23	and changed the glory of the incorruptible God for a likeness of an image of corruptible man and of birds and four-footed animals and reptiles.
B045C001V024	45	1	24	Therefore God also gave them up to uncleanness through the lusts of the own hearts, to dishonor their own bodies among themselves,
B045C001V025	45	1	25	who exchanged the truth of God for the lie, and worshipped and served the creature rather than the Creator, who is blessed forever. Amen.
B045C001V026	45	1	26	For this reason God gave them up to shameful lusts, for even their women exchanged the natural use for that which is contrary to nature,
B045C001V027	45	1	27	and likewise also the men, having forsaken the natural use of the woman, were inflamed by their lust for one another, men with men, committing what is shameful, and receiving in themselves the recompense which was fitting for their error.
B045C001V028	45	1	28	And just as they did not approve to have God in their knowledge, God gave them up to a reprobate mind, to do the things which are not fitting;
B045C001V029	45	1	29	having been filled with all unrighteousness, fornication, wickedness, greed, malice; full of envy, murder, strife, deceit, maliciousness; they are whisperers,
B045C001V030	45	1	30	slanderers, haters of God, insolent men, proud, braggarts, inventors of evil things, disobedient to parents,
B045C001V031	45	1	31	without understanding, untrustworthy, unloving, unforgiving, unmerciful;
B045C001V032	45	1	32	who, having known the righteous judgment of God, that those practicing such things are worthy of death, not only do them, but also approve of those who practice them.
B045C002V001	45	2	1	Therefore you are inexcusable, O man, everyone who judges, for in whatever you judge another you condemn yourself, for you who judge are practicing the same things.
B045C002V002	45	2	2	But we know that the judgment of God is according to truth upon those practicing such things.
B045C002V003	45	2	3	But do you suppose this, O man, you who judge those practicing such things yet doing them, that you will escape the judgment of God?
B045C002V004	45	2	4	Or do you despise the riches of His kindness and tolerance and patience, not knowing that the kindness of God leads you to repentance?
B045C002V005	45	2	5	But according to your hardness and impenitent heart you are storing up for yourself wrath in the day of wrath and revelation, and of the righteous judgment of God,
B045C002V006	45	2	6	who will recompense to each one according to his works:
B045C002V007	45	2	7	to those who by the endurance of good works are seeking glory and honor and incorruption-eternal life.
B045C002V008	45	2	8	But to those who are contentious, and who disobey the truth, but obey unrighteousness-indignation and wrath,
B045C002V009	45	2	9	tribulation and anguish, upon every soul of man that works evil, of the Jew first and also of the Greek;
B045C002V010	45	2	10	but glory, honor, and peace to everyone that works good, both to the Jew first and to the Greek.
B045C002V011	45	2	11	For there is no partiality with God.
B045C002V012	45	2	12	For all who have sinned without the law shall also perish without the law, and all who have sinned under the law shall be judged by the law
B045C002V013	45	2	13	(for [it is ]not the hearers of the law [who ]are righteous before God, but the doers of the law shall be justified;
B045C002V014	45	2	14	for whenever Gentiles, who do not have the law, by nature do what the law requires, these, not having the law, are a law unto themselves,
B045C002V015	45	2	15	who show the work of the law written in their hearts, their conscience witnessing with [them], and among themselves their thoughts accuse or even defend [them]),
B045C002V016	45	2	16	in the day when God shall judge the secrets of men according to my gospel through Jesus Christ.
B045C002V017	45	2	17	Behold, you are called a Jew, and rely on the law, and boast in God,
B045C002V018	45	2	18	and know His will, and approve the things that are more excellent, being instructed out of the law,
B045C002V019	45	2	19	and are convinced that you are a guide to the blind, a light to those in darkness,
B045C002V020	45	2	20	an instructor of the foolish, a teacher of the immature, having the embodiment of knowledge and of the truth in the law.
B045C002V021	45	2	21	You, therefore, who teach another, do you not teach yourself? You who preach that a man should not steal, do you steal?
B045C002V022	45	2	22	You who say, "Do not commit adultery,"do you commit adultery? You who abhor idols, do you commit sacrilege?
B045C002V023	45	2	23	You who boast in the law, do you dishonor God through the transgression of the law?
B045C002V024	45	2	24	For "The name of God is blasphemed among the Gentiles because of you,"just as it is written.
B045C002V025	45	2	25	For indeed circumcision profits if you keep the law; but if you are a transgressor of the law, your circumcision has become uncircumcision.
B045C002V026	45	2	26	Therefore, if an uncircumcised man keeps the righteous requirements of the law, will not his uncircumcision be counted for circumcision?
B045C002V027	45	2	27	And will not the physically uncircumcised, who keeps the law, judge you along with your written [code] and circumcision, as a lawbreaker?
B045C002V028	45	2	28	For he is not a Jew who is one outwardly, nor is circumcision that which is outward in flesh;
B045C002V029	45	2	29	but he [is] a Jew that [is one] inwardly; and circumcision is of the heart, in [the] spirit, not in [the ]letter, whose praise is not from men but from God.
B045C003V001	45	3	1	What then [is] the superiority of the Jew, or what is the profit of circumcision?
B045C003V002	45	3	2	Much in every way! First of all, that they were entrusted with the [very ]words of God!
B045C003V003	45	3	3	For what if some did not believe? Will their unbelief nullify the faithfulness of God?
B045C003V004	45	3	4	By no means! Indeed, let God be true but every man a liar, just as it is written: "That You may be justified in Your words, and You may prevail when You are judged."
B045C003V005	45	3	5	But if our unrighteousness demonstrates the righteousness of God, what shall we say? [Surely] God, the [One ]inflicting wrath is not unrighteous, is [He]? (I speak as a man).
B045C003V006	45	3	6	By no means! For otherwise how shall God judge the world?
B045C003V007	45	3	7	For if by my lie the truth of God has abounded to His glory, why am I also still judged as a sinner?
B045C003V008	45	3	8	And why not say, "Let us do evil so that good may come"?-just as we are slandered, and just as some affirm that we say. [The] judgment of whom is just.
B045C003V009	45	3	9	What then? Are we [any] better? Not at all. For we previously charged both Jews and Greeks that they are all under sin.
B045C003V010	45	3	10	Just as it is written: "There is none righteous, no not one,
B045C003V011	45	3	11	There is none who understands; there is none who seeks God.
B045C003V012	45	3	12	All [have ]turned aside; together they became unprofitable; there is not [one] doing kindness, there is not so much as one."
B045C003V013	45	3	13	"Their throat is an opened grave; with their tongues they deceived"; "[the ]poison of asps is under their lips";
B045C003V014	45	3	14	"Whose mouth is full of cursing and bitterness.
B045C003V015	45	3	15	Their feet are swift to shed blood;
B045C003V016	45	3	16	Ruin and misery are in their ways;
B045C003V017	45	3	17	And the way of peace they did not know.
B045C003V018	45	3	18	There is no fear of God before their eyes."
B045C003V019	45	3	19	Now we know that as many things as the law says, it speaks to those under the law, so that every mouth may be stopped, and all the world may become guilty before God.
B045C003V020	45	3	20	Therefore by works of the law no flesh shall be justified in His sight, for through the law [comes] [the] knowledge of sin.
B045C003V021	45	3	21	But now the righteousness of God apart from the law has been revealed, being witnessed to by the Law and the Prophets,
B045C003V022	45	3	22	even the righteousness of God, through [the] faithfulness of Jesus Christ, to all and upon all those that believe. For there is no distinction;
B045C003V023	45	3	23	for all have sinned and fall short of the glory of God,
B045C003V024	45	3	24	being justified freely by His grace through the redemption that is in Christ Jesus,
B045C003V025	45	3	25	whom God set forth as a propitiation through faith in His blood, for a demonstration of His righteousness through the passing over of the sins having previously committed, in the forbearance of God,
B045C003V026	45	3	26	for a demonstration of His righteousness in the present time, that He might be just and the justifier of he who has [the] faith of Jesus.
B045C003V027	45	3	27	Where then is the boasting? It is excluded. Through what law? Of works? No, but through the law of faith.
B045C003V028	45	3	28	Therefore we conclude that a man is justified by faith apart from works of the law.
B045C003V029	45	3	29	Or is He the God of the Jews only? But is He not also the God of the Gentiles? Yes, of the Gentiles also,
B045C003V030	45	3	30	since there is one God who will justify [the ]circumcision by faith, and the uncircumcised through faith.
B045C003V031	45	3	31	Therefore do we nullify the law through faith? By no means! On the contrary, we uphold [the] law.
B045C004V001	45	4	1	What then shall we say that Abraham our father has found according to the flesh?
B045C004V002	45	4	2	For if Abraham was justified by works, he has [grounds for] boasting, but not before God.
B045C004V003	45	4	3	For what does the Scripture say? "Abraham believed God, and it was credited to him as righteousness."
B045C004V004	45	4	4	Now to him who works, his wage is not reckoned as a gift, but as his due.
B045C004V005	45	4	5	But to him who does not work but believes on Him who justifies the ungodly, his faith is credited as righteousness,
B045C004V006	45	4	6	just as David also speaks of the blessing of the man to whom God credits righteousness apart from works:
B045C004V007	45	4	7	"Blessed [are] [they] whose lawless deeds have been forgiven, and whose sins have been covered;
B045C004V008	45	4	8	Blessed is the man to whom the LORD shall by no means impute sin."
B045C004V009	45	4	9	Does this blessing then come upon the circumcision, or also upon the uncircumcised? For we say that faith was credited to Abraham as righteousness.
B045C004V010	45	4	10	How then was it credited? While he was circumcised, or in uncircumcision? Not in circumcision, but in uncircumcision.
B045C004V011	45	4	11	And he received the sign of circumcision, a seal of the righteousness of the faith which [he had while ]in uncircumcision, so that he should be the father of all those that believe, although uncircumcised, so that righteousness should also be imputed to them,
B045C004V012	45	4	12	and the father of circumcision to those not only of circumcision, but also to those following in the steps of the faith which our father Abraham[ had while] in uncircumcision.
B045C004V013	45	4	13	For the promise that he should be heir of the world was not to Abraham or to his seed through [the] law, but through [the] righteousness of faith.
B045C004V014	45	4	14	For if those who are of [the] law are heirs, faith is made void and the promise has been nullified,
B045C004V015	45	4	15	because the law produces wrath; for where there is no law neither is there transgression.
B045C004V016	45	4	16	Therefore it is of faith that it may be according to grace, so that the promise might be sure to all the seed, not only to those[ ]of the law, but also to those of the faith of Abraham, who is the father of us all,
B045C004V017	45	4	17	(just as it is written, "I have appointed you a father of many nations") before God, whom he believed, the [One] who gives life to the dead and calls those things which are not as though they were;
B045C004V018	45	4	18	who, contrary to hope, on hope believed, so that he should become a father of many nations, according to what was spoken, "So shall your descendants be."
B045C004V019	45	4	19	And not weakening in faith, he did not consider his own body, already having been worn out (being about a hundred years old), and the deadness of Sarah's womb,
B045C004V020	45	4	20	he did not waver at the promise of God in unbelief, but was empowered by faith, giving glory to God,
B045C004V021	45	4	21	and being fully convinced that what He had promised He was also able to do.
B045C004V022	45	4	22	And therefore "it was credited to him as righteousness."
B045C004V023	45	4	23	Now it was not written for his sake alone that it was credited to him,
B045C004V024	45	4	24	but for us also, to whom it was going to be credited, those believing on Him who raised up Jesus our Lord from the dead,
B045C004V025	45	4	25	who was delivered up for our transgressions, and was raised for our justification.
B045C005V001	45	5	1	Therefore, having been justified by faith, we have peace with God through our Lord Jesus Christ,
B045C005V002	45	5	2	through whom we have also obtained access by faith into this grace in which we stand, and we rejoice in hope of the glory of God.
B045C005V003	45	5	3	And not only that, but we also rejoice in tribulations, knowing that tribulation produces endurance;
B045C005V004	45	5	4	and endurance, character; and character, hope.
B045C005V005	45	5	5	And hope does not put to shame, because the love of God has been poured out in our hearts by the Holy Spirit who was given to us.
B045C005V006	45	5	6	For while we were still weak, in due time Christ died for the ungodly.
B045C005V007	45	5	7	For scarcely on behalf of a righteous [man] will anyone die; yet perhaps for a good man someone might even dare to die.
B045C005V008	45	5	8	But God demonstrates His own love toward us, in that while we were still sinners, Christ died for us.
B045C005V009	45	5	9	Much more then, having now been justified by His blood, we shall be saved from wrath through Him.
B045C005V010	45	5	10	For if while we were enemies we were reconciled to God through the death of His Son, much more, having been reconciled, we shall be saved by His life.
B045C005V011	45	5	11	And not only that, but we also rejoice in God through our Lord Jesus Christ, through whom now we received the reconciliation.
B045C005V012	45	5	12	Therefore, just as through one man sin entered the world, and death through sin, and thus death passed to all men, because all sinned-
B045C005V013	45	5	13	(For until the law sin was in the world, but sin is not imputed when there is no law.
B045C005V014	45	5	14	Yet death reigned from Adam to Moses, even over those who did not sin according to the likeness of the transgression of Adam, who is a type of Him who was to come.
B045C005V015	45	5	15	But the free gift is not like the transgression. For if by the transgression of the one man many died, much more the grace of God and the gift by the grace of the one Man, Jesus Christ, abounded to the many.
B045C005V016	45	5	16	And the gift is not as by one having sinned. For the judgment [which came] from one [transgression resulted] in condemnation, but the free gift from many offenses [brought ] justification.
B045C005V017	45	5	17	For if by the transgression of the one man death reigned through the one [man], much more those receiving the abundance of the grace and of the gift of righteousness will reign in life through the One, Jesus Christ).
B045C005V018	45	5	18	So then, as through one [man's] transgression [judgment came] to all men, resulting in condemnation, even so through one [Man's] righteous act the free gift came to all men, resulting in justification of life.
B045C005V019	45	5	19	For through the disobedience of the one man the many were constituted sinners, so also through the obedience of the One many shall be constituted righteous.
B045C005V020	45	5	20	But [the] law came in alongside, so that the offense might abound. But where sin abounded, grace superabounded,
B045C005V021	45	5	21	so that just as sin reigned in death, so also grace might reign through righteousness to eternal life through Jesus Christ our Lord.
B045C006V001	45	6	1	What shall we say then? Shall we go on sinning so that grace may abound?
B045C006V002	45	6	2	By no means! We died to sin-How shall we live any longer in it?
B045C006V003	45	6	3	Or do you not know that as many [of us] as were baptized into Christ Jesus have been baptized into His death?
B045C006V004	45	6	4	Therefore we were buried with Him through baptism into death, so that just as Christ was raised from the dead through the glory of the Father, so we also should walk in newness of life.
B045C006V005	45	6	5	For if we have been united together in the likeness of His death, certainly we shall also be [in the likeness] of [His] resurrection;
B045C006V006	45	6	6	knowing this, that our old man was crucified [with Him], so that the body of sin may be done away with, [that] we should no longer serve sin.
B045C006V007	45	6	7	For he who has died has been justified from sin.
B045C006V008	45	6	8	But if we died with Christ, we believe that we also shall live together with Him,
B045C006V009	45	6	9	knowing that Christ, having been raised from the dead, no longer dies. Death is no longer master [over] Him.
B045C006V010	45	6	10	For what [death] He died, He died to sin once for all; but what [life] He lives, He lives to God.
B045C006V011	45	6	11	Likewise you also, consider yourselves to be dead indeed to sin, but alive to God in Christ Jesus our Lord.
B045C006V012	45	6	12	Therefore do not let sin reign in your mortal body, that you should obey it in its lusts,
B045C006V013	45	6	13	nor present your members as instruments of unrighteousness to sin, but present yourselves to God as being alive from the dead, and your members as instruments of righteousness to God.
B045C006V014	45	6	14	For sin shall not be master over you, for you are not under law but under grace.
B045C006V015	45	6	15	What then? Shall we sin because we are not under law but under grace? By no means!
B045C006V016	45	6	16	Do you not know that to whom you present yourselves as obedient slaves, you are slaves to whom you obey, whether of sin [resulting] in death, or of obedience [resulting] in righteousness?
B045C006V017	45	6	17	But thanks be to God, that though you used to be slaves of sin, yet you obeyed from [your] heart that form of doctrine to which you were delivered.
B045C006V018	45	6	18	And having been freed from sin, you became enslaved to righteousness.
B045C006V019	45	6	19	I speak in human terms on account of the weakness of your flesh. For just as you presented your members as slaves to uncleanness, and to lawlessness [resulting] in [more] lawlessness, so now present your members as slaves to righteousness [resulting] in sanctification.
B045C006V020	45	6	20	For when you were slaves of sin, you were free in regard to righteousness.
B045C006V021	45	6	21	So what fruit did you have then of which [things] you are now ashamed? For the end of those things is death.
B045C006V022	45	6	22	But now having been freed from sin, and having become enslaved to God, you have your fruit [resulting] in sanctification, and the end, eternal life.
B045C006V023	45	6	23	For the wages of sin [is] death, but the gift of God [is] eternal life in Christ Jesus our Lord.
B045C007V001	45	7	1	Or do you not know, brothers (for I speak to those knowing the law), that the law has jurisdiction over a man as long as he lives?
B045C007V002	45	7	2	For the woman who is under a man has been bound by law to the living husband. But if the husband should die, she is released from the law of the husband.
B045C007V003	45	7	3	So then, while the husband is living, she will be called an adulteress if she becomes [married] to a different husband; but if her husband should die, she is free from the law, so that she is not an adulteress, having become [married] to a different husband.
B045C007V004	45	7	4	Therefore, my brothers, you also were put to death to the law through the body of Christ, that you may be married to another-to Him who was raised from the dead, so that we might bear fruit to God.
B045C007V005	45	7	5	For when we were in the flesh, the sinful passions aroused through the law were at work in our members to bear fruit to death.
B045C007V006	45	7	6	But now we were released from the law, having died in [that] to which we were held fast, so that we should serve as slaves in the newness of the Spirit and not in the oldness of the letter.
B045C007V007	45	7	7	What shall we say then? Is the law sin? By no means! On the contrary, I would not have known sin except through the law. For I would not have known lust unless the law had said, "You shall not covet."
B045C007V008	45	7	8	But sin, taking opportunity through the commandment, produced in me every kind of lust. For apart from the law sin [was] dead.
B045C007V009	45	7	9	For I was alive apart from the law once, but when the commandment came, sin revived, but I died.
B045C007V010	45	7	10	And the commandment, which [was] to [bring] life, I found to [bring] death.
B045C007V011	45	7	11	For sin, taking opportunity by the commandment, deceived me, and by it, killed me.
B045C007V012	45	7	12	Therefore the law indeed is holy, and the commandment holy and righteous and good.
B045C007V013	45	7	13	Then has that which is good become death to me? By no means! But sin, that it might appear sin, was producing death in me through that which is good, so that sin through the commandment might become exceedingly sinful.
B045C007V014	45	7	14	For we know that the law is spiritual, but I am carnal, having been sold under sin.
B045C007V015	45	7	15	For what I am doing, I do not know. For what I want to do, I do not do; but what I hate, this I do.
B045C007V016	45	7	16	But if I do what I do not want to do, I agree with the law that [it is] good.
B045C007V017	45	7	17	But now [it is] no longer I [who] am doing it, but the sin living in me.
B045C007V018	45	7	18	For I know that in me (that is, in my flesh) nothing good dwells; for to will is present with me, but [how] to do the good, I do not find.
B045C007V019	45	7	19	For the good that I want to do I do not do; but the evil I do not want to do, this I practice.
B045C007V020	45	7	20	But if I do what I do not want to do, it is no longer I [who] do it, but the sin living in me.
B045C007V021	45	7	21	Therefore I find this law, that [when] I wish to do the right[ thing], evil is right there with me.
B045C007V022	45	7	22	For I delight in the law of God in my inner being.
B045C007V023	45	7	23	But I see a different law in my members, waging war against the law of my mind, and capturing me by the law of sin which is in my members.
B045C007V024	45	7	24	O wretched man that I am! Who shall deliver me from this body of death?
B045C007V025	45	7	25	I thank God through Jesus Christ our Lord! So then, I myself with the mind serve the law of God, but with the flesh the law of sin.
B045C008V001	45	8	1	[There is] therefore now no condemnation to those who are in Christ Jesus, who do not walk according to the flesh, but according to the Spirit.
B045C008V002	45	8	2	For the law of the Spirit of life in Christ Jesus has set me free from the law of sin and of death.
B045C008V003	45	8	3	For what [was] impossible [for] the law to do in that it was weak through the flesh, God [did] by sending His own Son in the likeness of sinful flesh, and concerning sin, He condemned sin in the flesh,
B045C008V004	45	8	4	so that the righteous requirement of the law might be fulfilled in us who do not walk according to the flesh but according to the Spirit.
B045C008V005	45	8	5	For those who are fleshly set their minds on the things of the flesh, but those [who live] according to the Spirit, the things of the Spirit.
B045C008V006	45	8	6	For the mind set on the flesh is death, but the mind set on the Spirit is life and peace.
B045C008V007	45	8	7	Because the mind set on the flesh is hostile toward God; for it does not submit to the law of God, nor indeed can it.
B045C008V008	45	8	8	And those that are in the flesh cannot please God.
B045C008V009	45	8	9	But you are not in the flesh but in the Spirit, if indeed the Spirit of God dwells in you. But if anyone does not have the Spirit of Christ, he is not His.
B045C008V010	45	8	10	But if Christ is in you, the body indeed is dead because of sin, but the Spirit is alive because of righteousness.
B045C008V011	45	8	11	But if the Spirit of Him who raised Jesus from the dead dwells in you, He who raised Christ from the dead will also give life to your mortal bodies through His Spirit indwelling in you.
B045C008V012	45	8	12	Therefore, brothers, we are debtors-not to the flesh, to live according to the flesh.
B045C008V013	45	8	13	For if you live according to the flesh you shall die; but if by [the] Spirit you put to death the practices of the body, you will live.
B045C008V014	45	8	14	For as many as are led by the Spirit of God, these are sons of God.
B045C008V015	45	8	15	For you did not receive the spirit of bondage again unto fear, but you received the Spirit of adoption by whom we cry out, "Abba, Father."
B045C008V016	45	8	16	The Spirit Himself bears witness with our spirit that we are children of God.
B045C008V017	45	8	17	And if children, then heirs-heirs of God and joint heirs with Christ, if indeed we suffer together, so that we may also be glorified together.
B045C008V018	45	8	18	For I consider that the sufferings of this present time are not worthy [to be compared] with the coming glory to be revealed in us.
B045C008V019	45	8	19	For the earnest expectation of the creation eagerly awaits the unveiling of the sons of God.
B045C008V020	45	8	20	For the creation was subjected to futility, not willingly, but on account of Him who subjected it in hope;
